Reasoning: The paper focuses on analyzing the structures and evolutions of reciprocal and parasocial edges in online social networks, exploring the factors that influence the formation of reciprocal edges, and predicting whether a parasocial edge will turn into a reciprocal one. This involves analyzing large-scale social network datasets, modeling edge prediction as an outlier detection problem, and evaluating the proposed approach against previous methods. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.SOC (Computational Social Science), followed by cs.IR (Information Retrieval), cs.LG (Machine Learning), and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
